You need to fetch each row individually.  In other words you need to call `fetch()` in a loop to access each row (alternatively, you could `fetchAll()`, but that is not appropriate if you intend to iterate/process the data on the same &quot;layer&quot; of the script).

See this reference: https://phpdelusions.net/pdo/fetch_modes#FETCH_OBJ

You are iterating the properties and values within a single row.  However, you should be iterating the rows and manually accessing the values by property name.

Untested suggestion:

    while ($row = $stmt-&gt;fetch(PDO::FETCH_OBJ)) {
        $arrProcessLable[] = $row-&gt;status;
        $arrProcessPer[] = round(($row-&gt;count * 100) / $total, 2);
    }



---

Additional notes:

- You don&#39;t need to alias `projects.status as status` because the column `projects.status` will be given the property `status` in the result set anyhow -- the table names are omitted.

- MySQL has suitable mathematical functions that would permit you to perform all calculations before php touches the result set. This may be something of interest for you.

- Lastly, if you only want to fetch once `-&gt;fetchAll(PDO::FETCH_KEY_PAIR)` looks like something useful, since you are pairing statuses with their counts.  Refer to the above link and scroll down.

