Use `DateTimePicker.Value` instead of `DateTimePicker.Text`. If you only want the date part, you could use `DateTimePicker.Value.Date`.

[`DateTimePicker.Value`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.windows.forms.datetimepicker.value) is the actual `DateTime` object assigned to the control, whereas [`DateTimePicker.Text`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.windows.forms.datetimepicker.text) is the `Value` property with formatting applied. Using `Value` directly saves you from having to convert the `Text` to a `DateTime` first.

You should also use a parameterized query, as others have noted.

```lang-csharp
string query = &quot;Insert into myTable Values (@myDate)&quot;;
using(SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
{
    using(SqlCommand command = new SqlCommand(query, connection))
    {
        command.Parameters.AddWithValue(&quot;myDate&quot;, dateTimePicker1.Value);       
    }
}
```

